316 supervised community confinement as provided in subsection 2 but who has not been
327 approved for transfer to appeal that determination to the commissioner.
3 Sec. 2. 34-A MRSA §3036-A, sub-§2-B is enacted to read:
4 2-B. Additional process for prisoners incarcerated for crime committed against
5 family or household member or dating partner. In addition to the process required by
6 subsection 2-A, in determining whether a prisoner incarcerated for a crime that was
7 committed against a family or household member, as defined in Title 19-A, section 4102,
8 subsection 6, or dating partner, as defined in Title 19-A, section 4102, subsection 4, is
9 approved for transfer, the process under this subsection must provide for the following:
10 A. Review and consideration of the results of any validated, evidence-based domestic
11 violence risk assessment, including one that has been completed by a law enforcement
12 officer in accordance with Title 19-A, section 4114, subsection 6, paragraph E as part
13 of the criminal case for which the prisoner is incarcerated; and
14 B. Notification of the application for transfer to supervised community confinement
15 to the district attorney of the county in which the conviction was entered as well as a
16 local domestic violence resource center.
17 Sec. 3. 34-A MRSA §3036-A, sub-§3, ¶K is enacted to read:
18 K. When required by the commissioner and to the extent that the commissioner
19 determines that the prisoner has the financial resources, the prisoner shall continue to
20 pay any outstanding victim restitution at a level similar to what the prisoner would have
21 had to pay if the prisoner had remained incarcerated at a department correctional
22 facility.
23 Sec. 4. 34-A MRSA §3036-A, sub-§10, as amended by PL 2023, c. 659, §2, is
24 further amended to read:
25 10. Terminally ill or incapacitated prisoner. With the consent of the prisoner, the
26 commissioner may transfer a prisoner committed to the department from a correctional
27 facility to supervised community confinement without meeting the eligibility requirements
28 of subsection 2, paragraphs B and C and without meeting the criteria or fulfilling the
29 process provided for under subsection subsections 2‑A and 2-B if the department's director
30 of medical care has determined that the prisoner has a terminal or severely incapacitating
31 medical condition or has a worsening prognosis that is likely to result in a terminal or
32 severely incapacitating medical condition and that care outside a correctional facility is
33 medically appropriate. Except as set out in this subsection, the prisoner must live in a
34 hospital or other appropriate care facility, such as a nursing facility, residential care facility
35 or a facility that is a licensed hospice program pursuant to Title 22, section 8622, approved
36 by the commissioner. As approved by the commissioner, the prisoner may receive hospice
37 services from an entity licensed pursuant to Title 22, chapter 1681, subchapter 1 or other
38 care services provided by an entity approved by the commissioner and, subject to approval
39 by the commissioner, may live at home while receiving these services. The commissioner
40 may exempt a prisoner transferred to supervised community confinement pursuant to this
41 subsection from any mandatory condition under subsection 3 that the commissioner
42 determines to be inapplicable. The prisoner shall provide any information pertaining to the
43 prisoner's medical condition or care that is requested by the commissioner at any time while
44 the prisoner is on supervised community confinement. If the commissioner determines that
